04025nam a22005295i 9780226356549DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015039772  a97802263565497 a10.7208/97802263565492doi  a(DE-B1597)550175  a(OCoLC)957590706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aTR114b.B44 2016 4aTR114b.B44 2016 7aPHO0000002bisacsh04a770.9562231 aBehdad, Ali, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCamera Orientalis :bReflections on Photography of the Middle East /cAli Behdad. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b4 color plates, 80 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. camera Orientalis -- t1. the orientalist photograph -- t2. the tourist, the collector, and the curator on the lives and afterlives of ottoman-era photography -- t3. the politics of resident photography in the middle east reflections on antoin sevruguin’s photographs of qajar-era Iran0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades after its invention in 1839, photography was inextricably linked to the Middle East. Introduced as a crucial tool for Egyptologists and Orientalists who needed to document their archaeological findings, the photograph was easier and faster to produce in intense Middle Eastern light—making the region one of the original sites for the practice of photography. A pioneering study of this intertwined history, Camera Orientalis traces the Middle East’s influences on photography’s evolution, as well as photography’s effect on Europe’s view of “the Orient.” Considering a range of Western and Middle Eastern archival material from the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Ali Behdad offers a rich account of how photography transformed Europe’s distinctly Orientalist vision into what seemed objective fact, a transformation that proved central to the project of European colonialism. At the same time, Orientalism was useful for photographers from both regions, as it gave them a set of conventions by which to frame exotic Middle Eastern cultures for Western audiences. Behdad also shows how Middle Eastern audiences embraced photography as a way to foreground status and patriarchal values while also exoticizing other social classes. An important examination of previously overlooked European and Middle Eastern photographers and studios, Camera Orientalis demonstrates that, far from being a one-sided European development, Orientalist photography was the product of rich cultural contact between the East and the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aOrientalism in art. 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspectszMiddle East. 0aPhotographyzMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226356549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226356549.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles